segments.text: office at the Austin Redevelopment Authority.
Thomas is the executive director of this authority, and today is January 8, 1981.
We are interviewing Thomas because of two reasons.
One, he is the immediate past assistant planning director for the city of Austin, and two,
is the current executive director of the Austin Redevelopment Authority.

The topic of the interview is the planning process in Austin, going back as far in history as your personal experience will enable you to make accurate statements regarding events that have occurred that have been important and have influenced
the process and the production of planned documents in Austin.
So with that, Tom, we've got the list of preliminary questions in front of us.
If you'd like to start with those that you are confident about and just simply bypass those that we can find through library research or whatever.
Go ahead.
The first issue, I guess, is what my personal knowledge extends to, and that's to 1975, five years ago.
I have some knowledge, of course, of what happened prior to that, but personally involved in watching what's happened.
I guess I'd say that, from my own experience, probably 1972 would be the beginning of accurate statements, if you would.
When you arrived from Texarkana.
Texarkana.
Okay, first legislative authorization, comprehensive plan.
That's easy to check.
I don't remember that.
I think it's 1926.
Most recent comprehensive plan approval occurred in 1977.
Prior to that was 1961.
1961 was done by a consultant.
What we weren't sure about was who did the 1961 master plan.
1961 plan.
It's published and so the author is shown.
It's only been since 1977 as we look at, let's look at question three.

The 1977 plan set forth policies for periodic review, and that's an annual review conducted by the Planning Commission, submitted to the City Council, and then reviewed, of course, by other commissions and boards in the city.
Last night, in the 1980 review statement from the Planning Department's perspective was presented to the Planning Commission.
So under that plan, there is an annual review and an analysis of performance, what they did and didn't do, and how the objectives are being reached or not being reached.
Between the first two plans and when there wasn't any approved system of review, what was done to evaluate, let's say, the first plan?
Very little.
I'm not aware of any evaluations that occurred.
The land use map was pretty well adhered to.
There wasn't anything else in there other than some population projections and things, a typical 701 plan.
And there was criteria in that plan for establishing industrial districts within the extraterritorial jurisdiction and things of that nature that were used.
Once in a while there would be a revision in the master plan, and that revision generally dealt with that land use category.
of what was an area for low density, high density housing, what area would be industrial or non-industrial.
More or less minor revisions rather than entire concepts.
Piecemeal.
Exactly.
And so 1970, 71 is when they first determined that that was insufficient and so a new plan was undertaken.
Partially answered the next question, that is, Austin's comprehensive plans have been revised before.
What was the process that took place in order to have this revision?
We're speaking about the current one.
In 1972, the city planning department, the planning commission, and I suspect at that time the council also, made a decision that they needed a new master plan.
And it first started by the development of a goals program for what this community wanted itself to be, known as the Austin Tomorrow Plan program.
went on for five years, with many, many meetings, and many, many technical reports, and a tremendous amount of citizen participation.
The result of all that activity then brought forth a five-chapter master plan in 1977, which was adopted by Kelso.
But it was a citizen-based, goals, objectives, policies master plan.
We'll talk about the citizens action later, I imagine.
As far as characterizing the planning style of Austin, would you say that it conducts comprehensive planning or one of the other various styles that cities use from time to time?
The overall development of the master plan, the 1977 master plan, was comprehensive.
That went as far as
goals and objectives and policies.
And those were, as I said, comprehensive community-wide.
The big issues, growth, development, style, shape of the city.
Moving beyond that to specifics then, the city has done incremental planning.
It has selected areas of the community, the Lake Austin area, and looked at that in a microcosm.
It has looked at corridors, it has looked at creek,
areas.
And so one at a time they've been reviewed.
And there's two of them under review right now.
The plans are being developed.
So it's been incremental in the sense of looking at different areas that are of a smaller scale rather than responding to different problems in that as they come along.
It's usually incremental as far as area goes, different city areas.
As far as the master plan itself is concerned, that's true.
As far as the issues and conflicts that occur, those are case by case.
When was the first zoning ordinance in Austin?
I believe it was 1926.
And that was done approximately at the same time as the legislative, as the city's comprehensive plan was approved then?
Or shortly thereafter?
I believe that's true.
I don't have the documents anymore, but
There was a master plan done in the 1924-25 area.

As far as administrative procedures and planning program elements, how does Austin, what does Austin use for implementing the community plan and different master plans that it's had throughout the broad area?
Yeah, first of all of course it uses, it uses zoning.
It uses subdivision control and
to a great deal that uses its capital improvements program in selecting investment based upon the master plan and its provisions.
There's been violations of that consistently in the past three years.
But the master plan was intended to guide the CIP process.
And in fact, the charter requires a provision that no CIP
can ever be funded and no project undertaken which is in conflict with the city's master plan.
Have there been any precedents where conflicts, project conflicts with the master plan and it has been brought to court then?
No, they've not been to court.
What has happened is that the master plan has been amended to remove the conflict.
Then of course on the other side, projects have been dropped too.
How has the organizational structure of the
Austin Planning Department evolved and the planning process evolved over the years?
Well, my experience, as I said, is relatively recent, maybe 1972.
I don't know the arrangement.
The charter provides that there be a planning director and a planning department and sets forth the basic responsibilities of that department.
It's organized as a line department of the city of Austin.
It's independent of public works, engineering, and all the others.
The department head reports directly to the assistant city manager, and then ultimately on to the deputy city manager and the city manager himself.
Its organization includes processing of subdivision flats and zoning, and then the development of long-range plans and special studies.
What type of liaison is there between the Planning Department and the legislative body that it lends advice to that is, I imagine, Austin City Council?
Well, the Planning Department is charged with support and staffing of the Planning Commission and the Historic Landmarks Commission.

the actions taken by those two groups whom the planning department supports directly then goes to the city council the planning department represents those boards as well as its own opinions before the council but it does directly support those two commissions and then there's an ongoing goals committee group of citizens that is somewhat dormant today that meets periodically and the planning department provides some staff to them their purpose
quite appropriately, at least in the 77 concept, is they're the watchdogs of the plan.
Their charge is to review and keep track of what's going on in the city and make comments as to its applicability to the master plan.
You mentioned earlier that citizen groups and action groups have played a great role in adoption of Austin's plan 2000, where
one of the last master plans that have been adopted.
Would you say they played a valuable role as far as input went?
Did they have direct access to people in the planning department?
Yes.
Yes.

In fact, prior to the Austin Tomorrow Program, citizen participation, I'm told, was independent groups and individuals who would state their cases to the Planning Commission and try to prevail when their issues were deemed to be
important.

With the coming of the Tomorrow Program, these were formalized and the city began to formally recognize neighborhood groups and chart territory under which they would be consulted and actually become a neighborhood activist and there's some 65 of those that have occurred and been chartered, if you will, recognized by the city since the Tomorrow Plan began.
That

went further now that any time a zoning change occurs or anything, the cognizant neighborhood group that is recognized by the city is given special notices to allow them to come and participate in those activities.
Are those citizens groups rather structured and active?
Or it would depend on which of the 65 groups I imagine you were dealing with.
Some would have more of an active interest and some would be more passive.
That's true.
There are neighborhood groups that are not very active.
The city requires for recognition that they have a set of bylaws, a membership, that they show that they are representative of the neighborhood they claim to represent.
There is.
Beyond that group, there is an Austin Neighborhoods Council made up of presidents or chairmen of each of these neighborhood groups.
who bring a unified voice then to face the city council or others when an overall city issue is involved.

Because on one level the individual is worried about his district, but through the neighborhood's council they are then able to deal with the overall city issues like capital improvements programs, utility policies, and things that affect everyone.
I would imagine from the type of association that that is, that is on a neighborhood level,
that there can be quite a bit as far as special interest goes to a neighborhood and it would be hard for any one of the presidents to have any kind of community-wide interest.
Has this been a problem as far as citizen input goes?
The Neighborhoods Council has been most active in providing a forum and additional support for an issue that faces one or two neighborhoods.
As an example,
a certain particular zoning or transportation proposal may impact negatively one neighborhood but be beneficial to three or four others.
They provide a forum among themselves to come up with either rational compromises or present a unified front.
They do and are expected to be very suspicious and very serving of the neighborhood they're in.
But neighborhood issues such as
CIP and where we have elections and that.
They act as a sounding board and a compromise group to come up with an overall plan.
They've been effective in that.
They've also provided a training ground for people who seek council or commission appointments because they get to know the issues from their perspective.
Now the neighborhood groups have been characteristically antagonistic of business.
because they represent the residential sector of the community and not the business sector of the community.
Even those that are in leadership positions in citizen groups are typically amateurs when it comes to planning.
They have an idea of what their interests might be.
They may even have an interest in what Austin's, may even have some good input on what Austin's future ought to be.
But in the case where professional planners can see that
their input is for their own benefit and short-sighted, for one example.
Is that overridden by people in the planning department or is it still taken into account when the advice is formulated?
Well, Austin may again be unique in some respects because many of the people who are in leadership positions in the neighborhood groups do carry professional planning credentials.
They have the education, experience, and many are employed in professional planning organizations.
When they present an issue or wish to testify on a particular zoning case, subdivision, or whatever, their comments are their own.
They do not gain particular credibility with the city staff because the staff has its own position that it must, and it does, project
The Planning Commission then reviews, and here's testimony from many people, they independently make their position, the city staff makes its own, and there's no filtering of that.
There may be conflict, and that has happened in many cases where the staff has felt
for other good reasons that that was an inappropriate decision or inappropriate position.
They'll so state in theirs.
The neighborhood group makes its counter proposal and then the Planning Commission and Council make a decision.
That's been characteristic of Austin.
Cities in Texas have each had their own unique history in Austin, especially since it's been the capital of the state.
And there are several events that can be followed as far as
to draw some kind of comparison between cities in Texas.
And several events will have played different roles as far as, and the role of planning within those events can be significant.
Austin was founded in what year?
And that was, was it originally planned or plotted out?
It was plotted out under the Republic of Texas to be the capital of the state.
There was no town in existence when it occurred.
Was it a state body then that did the original platting or was it done by a consultant or an individual?
It was done by a surveyor hired by, I believe, Sam Houston.
But at that time, Texas was a republic, an independent nation.
And the charge from the history of this community was that they had chosen the site central to the entire state and decided that the city would be here and then the
the elected groups to the Republic.
The President of the Republic then selected the surveyor who laid out the original city, which was a mile square, which we're sitting in right now.
I imagine other cities in Texas that were already established at the time and already might have had claims to be the capital had some
there was some conflict as far as creating a new city that was to serve as the capital republic.
Is that true?
Well, in 1839, I believe the largest city in Texas was San Antonio.
At that point in time, there were few cities, obviously.
It was a totally frontier state.
Having just gone through the 1836 Alamo, the
fight for independence from Mexico.
It was a frontier state.
So, there was to be a capital, there was not to be a fight from existing cities.
And so the agreement was that there should be a capital central to the state, accessible to all of its citizens, that did not put one city against another.
And I believe the records indicate that
it was the general consensus that a new city be formed and that it be done.
And of course after looking at many sites around the state, this was the site that was chosen.
Have there been any significant city or county or state fairs or exhibitions held in Austin where planning has had a significant role?
I'm not aware of any.
Austin has always been the capital, but I'm not aware of any particular
of centennials or anything that occurred here.
I'm sure there was a centennial in 1939, but I'm not aware of what it was.
How about major conventions?
Has Austin been a site?
Austin has not been a site of major conventions.
It has, because of its size, has not been able to attract, primarily because it has a lack of hotel facilities.
It has adequate

more than adequate transportation access, but the Chamber of Commerce has repeatedly told us that the lack of hotels, and of course there's no convention facility to hold a large convention in Austin.
People have gone to San Antonio and Dallas before.
Is that an element that is addressed in the master plan?
Is that something that's desired as a goal?
to grow to the size where that kind of operation could be feasible and conventions could be attracted.
There have been several elections in this city to propose the construction of a modern, large convention facility to take advantage of this location and of course the state capital itself.
There has been expressed a great deal of support for having major conventions in Austin if the facilities were available.
In 1972, I believe, is the year in which an election was placed before the voters to build a convention facility, and it was defeated.
There has been continual discussion since that time.
It has been widely discussed throughout all the business and residential communities.
But to this date, there has not been a successful vote to do that.
You mentioned earlier that Austin did not exist, and it was selected as a site for the Capitol.
Can you tell me what other functions in those frontier days Austin served other than being the capital let's say for commerce, trade, or transportation or that?
Well, when it was chartered as a city, Austin didn't serve any economic function.
It was a governmental seat, pure and simple.
It was a stage line.
between San Antonio and North Texas and on up to St. Louis and that area.

There were instances of some fringes of the cattle drives from South Texas, but not very many, because the cattle trail was east of, it was east of Austin, from the South Plains up through Amarillo, Abilene, east and west.
I was thinking west.
Yeah, some east, some west.
The Fort Worth
Railhead of course was east coming out of the Cape Ranch area.
Then the very far south and west Texas groups through Abilene and on up into Kansas and Omaha and places like that.
But to my knowledge until the coming of the railroad there was no great economic activity here.
It was a water supply sufficient to support a community and it was centrally located in the state.
What impact did the coming of the railroad have on Austin?
And what relationship did it have to other Texas cities as a railroad hub?
Well, the railroad killed cities in Texas by bypassing some.
It made others by making them new places for commerce.
For Austin, as I can see it, it never had a tremendous economic benefit because we weren't a railhead.
We were not a great agricultural area either.
It provided another means of transportation to and from the state capital to conduct the state business.
That's about the extent that I would know.
Was there any increase in state business as a result of the coming railroad or expansion of state government in relation to that?
Well, as the state grew, I think the railway
The railroad was one indication of the growth of the state and the importance of the state capital, and it may have been a solution to the symptom that was already occurring as the state was growing.
As you look around, of course, since 1886, the new state capital, which was built after the original one burned,

There's been continual expansion of state government, and it has been a, up until today anyway, the state of Texas has chosen to centralize its offices in Austin, unlike other states who put its major offices in many different cities.
Texas has not yet done that.
They have discussed it.
I don't know if they're planning to do it, but to date, all of the headquarters of all of the state agencies are all right here.
Texas, Austin has always been dependent upon the state as an employer.
Let's talk briefly about the federal government, specifically military influences in Austin.
Can you tell me if the World Wars have had a significant impact on planning in Austin due to, let's say, new military bases and influx of population resulting, or housing?
I don't think they have, though.
Prior to World War II, the only significant military establishment was Camp Mabry, which is the home of the Texas National Guard.
And it has not had a tremendous influx of anything.
It was a reservation set aside for that many, many, many, many years ago.
World War II, the Bergstrom Air Force Base was created outside the city, at a pretty good distance from the city.
We've only now grown to encompass it.
There has been housing that has resulted as that base has come up and gone down, and some of South Austin reflects that.
But if you say major today in relation to 500,000 people living in the area, there is no dominance of military installations.
So even in the case of the latter Air Force Base, planning conducted by Austin City did not need to consider the consequences of military population?
coming into the area?
It does not appear that they have because we have the state highway system serves that facility.
That was outside the domain of the city.

The development of residential areas in proximity to that Air Force base have resulted in severe noise impacts which indicates that there was a somewhat of an ignorance of the effect of that base on what it would do in residential
land.
And right now we have significant noise impacts and problems in the East Austin area as a result of the operation of military jets.
During the 1930s, during the Great Depression, New Deal financing as a result of New Deal programs had a great impact on Texas cities.
Can you tell me what impact, from what you know, WPA and funding for planning and development had on Austin during that time?
I don't know about any planning and development that occurred.
The city hall was built during that era.
It is a WPA project.
The federal courthouse is another.
I'm not aware of too many other specifics.
We do not have any flood control districts that I'm aware of like San Antonio River that was a WPA project.
I'm not sure what the system for the dams of the Highland Lakes was about.

Something that you're well versed in and probably address is the impact of urban renewal in Austin and what role the city has played as far as having people write grants and use available federal funding as a resource for stimulating local development.
Could you say something about that?
Austin was extremely active in the urban renewal programs.
It had five urban renewal, very significant urban renewal projects.
Today there are two of which have not yet totally been completed.
It was a major development activity that led to the expansion of the Capitol Complex.
It was a major development activity that led to the expansion of the University of Texas.
It was a major development activity that led to the beautification and saving of Waller Creek.
And then in East Austin,
There are three areas in which it had a tremendous impact on the removal of slums and blight and replatting in the typical sense.
But there are some unique factors in the Austin Urban Renewal Program that are not generally known even by Austinites.
Among those, the LBJ Library is located on urban renewal land.
The expansion of the university, the Super Drum, Brackenridge Hospital, all of those
lands were made available through the use of the urban renewal power, which is very, very significant.
It has recently come to light that there have been problems with accountability of funding that Austin has received from the federal government.
What do you see as the prospect for urban renewal and federal funding in Austin City?
As a result of that, how has planning been affected by the problems that Austin has had recently?
Well, the Urban Renewal Program, of course, expired in 1974, so the possibility of a rebirth of urban renewal is remote unless new federal legislation is prepared.
Funding problems today result in the Community Development Program.
The lack of funding currently, it's not been a long period, four or five months without funding, have resulted in the impairment of
rehabilitation programs to assist neighborhoods in keeping those neighborhoods viable living environments.
They've had some effect on planning, but not very much.
The planning function in the city of Austin has been self-sufficient and supported by the city itself and has never really depended heavily on federal funds for its operation.
As far as projects that
planners have envisioned for Austin that have been affected by this?
What kind of accommodations are being made to adjust goals and timeframes?
Well, you're talking about the cut off the funds or the...
There don't appear to be any adjustments to be made, really.
The majority of the funds that have been cut off affect housing rehabilitation, which is an ongoing, forever problem.
There have not been, because of the restrictive use of the funds, any great new community-wide type projects that were planned using these funds.
So it's not had an effect on those.
The funds are restricted in their use anyway.
There has been ongoing planning, continues to be, for I think the convention center.
There's been discussions of a new city hall.
There's ongoing development on Town Lake.
All of that's privately and publicly supported, apart from any federal funding.
But there is a significant impact when you consider that five or six months of rehabilitation activity has had to stop, and that affects hundreds of families.
